         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">9/10/87 ¶  ¶ The plant, to which you refer as such a troublesome weed, dear Mr Crawford, is the Modiola multifida, a native of North-America. ¶  ¶ I presume, the tall somewhat pendulous Bamboo, to whi...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">87.10.09a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Alexander Crawford</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Archives, University of New England, Armidale, NSW.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">9/10/87</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The plant, to which you refer as such a troublesome weed, dear Mr Crawford, is the <name key="Modiola%20multifida">Modiola multifida</name>, a native of North-America.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I presume, the tall somewhat pendulous Bamboo, to which you refer, is a cultivated species, as never yet any Bambusaceaus plant has been found or recorded from in N.S.W. or even in the southern parts of Queensland as wild, though one kind occurs as indigenous near Trinity-Bay,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Qld.</p>
               </note> and one, my <name key="Bambusa%20Arnhemica">Bambusa Arnhemica</name>, in the Kimberley-Country.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>WA.</p>
               </note> Should there be a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">native</hi>
               </seg> Bamboo on the MacLeay-River,<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>NSW.</p>
               </note> then I would be greatly pleased to get portion of the leaves and some flower and grains of it, also a description of soil, height, color of stem &amp;c</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Such data, as you give about the durability of the Eucal. corymbosa are of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">great importance</hi>
               </seg>, particularly so, as you can be always relied on for the identification of the trees. By all means give me any such information, as I can utilize it under your honored name already in the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">early</hi>
               </seg> part of 1888, when a <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">new edition</hi>
               </seg> of the "select plants" is to appear, still further augmented.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B88.13.02, p. 148: <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Eucalyptus%20corymbosa">Eucalyptus corymbosa</name>
                     </seg>. 'Fence-posts from this tree showed hardly any decay after 40 years (R. Crawford)'. (Crawford's given names were Alexander Robert; it is not known why M chose to use the second initial.) The passage does not appear in the next, 1891 edition of the work.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am quite touched with your generosity towards the Expedition. I merely sent the circular, to show you our <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">intentions</hi>
               </seg>. I am so sorry to hear of your adversities, and all the more sympathize, because I am less prosperous now than when I came as a young Doctor in 1847, though never speculating or entertaining</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Bambusa%20Arnhemica">Bambusa Arnhemica</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Eucalyptus%20corymbosa">Eucalyptus corymbosa</name>
            </p>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Modiola%20multifida">Modiola multifida</name>
            </p>
         </div>
